0–Female":"1280–Afdød","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"omkring 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1272–1320":"circa 1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Overleden","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"circa 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1272–1320":"about 1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"about 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stafford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Stafford (Staffordshire), but occasionally from other places with similar names, such as Stafford House in Ifield (Sussex), possibly East and West Stowford in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Stafford was born about 1272, in Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Isabel Stafford. He died in 1320, in Amblecote, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"Abt 1272–1320":"umbes 1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"umbes 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1272–1320":"noin 1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"noin 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1272–1320":"environ 1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1272–1320":"1272–1320","Abt 1272":"environ 1272","1302":"1302","1320":"1320","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William de Stafford est né environ 1272, à Bra